Republican strategy to resist Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, arguing that cases of electoral falsification in the United States are rarer than deaths from lightning strikes.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in a decade.
One thing can be said with confidence: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have been enacting laws since 2009 that complicate the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon gained new momentum after the November 2010 elections, which brought the Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills were passed restricting voting rights in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register a voter on the day of his will, and deprive citizens with criminal convictions of the right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills obliging voters to present photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, that is, 21 million people who have reached the voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by their state government body.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Electoral students who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use a photo ID issued by their school in several states.
The same states, however, allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mainly for Republicans, to use the credentials issued by these clubs for voting.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship for voting.
This is the first time such a requirement has been introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the voting of Latin American people.
It is estimated that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated laws in 2011 to abolish voter registration on voting day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those wishing to register.
This restriction did not go without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to add about 10 million citizens to the lists.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states passed laws aimed at shortening the early voting period.
During the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted early were African-American, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the state's total electorate.
The same thing happened to people from Latin America.
Representing only 11% of voters, they accounted for 24% of citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, who made up 76% of the electorate, only 46% of those who voted early were white.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters actively oppose the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several draft laws were vetoed by the Democratic governors.
The most ambiguous laws were suspended with the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This allowed to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo ID.
However, the new rules, which came into force, will certainly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics of the Democrats denounce the bias of the laws that were passed, seeing them as an obvious focus on influencing the 2012 election results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the Electoral College to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with confidence that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
