Therefore, I would recommend taking a test starting at age 50, or at age 40, if one of the direct relatives had prostate cancer.
Men of African American descent are also at increased risk.
The key is to make the right decision as soon as the cancer is detected.
Cancer can be both aggressive and sluggish.
The patient needs to explain the degree of risk of his cancer, offering him possible options, without mandatory treatment of prostate cancer, which does not pose a threat to life in the long run, and making a choice, in these cases, in favor of active monitoring of the disease.
