Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, the report that scientists may have been able to detect the Higgs boson caused a real stir - and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, not much or little.
Furthermore, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or at least the "least imperfect" description of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not been discovered experimentally before.
But physicists are not quite sure that it is the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at one major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although for complete certainty some data is not yet enough.
Let's imagine that we are talking about the Higgs boson, since the chances of making mistakes seem minimal, and see what it means.
There is, in this world, one law that is absolutely inevitable, that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to circumvent this rule, do not even try too hard, otherwise hurt yourself.
But although particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that there is also one law of a similar nature in it: the Pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" is, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
On this basis, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find decent citizens, called fermions, who prudently obey the Pauli principle.
In the other are the bosons, a vile band of anarchists who have no respect for anything, at least for this principle, which means that they can calmly find themselves in the same place at the same time.
According to the site (by the way, quite unusual) Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratory, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and "particles of force", through which the main forces of nature are distributed and to which the Higgs boson in some way belongs.
These same bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it’s because of one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or “particle of light,” which is the “courier” of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a single particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “breaks” the electromagnetic field at that particular place, like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" is born an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons of the "force carriers".
A more stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "broken".
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, one must reach very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only shake a very large stone.
That’s why we need a huge particle accelerator like the one operated at CERN – the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! – to achieve such huge energies.
An analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, while others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never keep itself on the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like a photon, by the way) do not.
So, what can all these studies “bring” to you, asks Mrs. Plamondon?
In science, they are used to test the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to detect a discrepancy between the results of observations and the predictions of SM.
In addition, some of them are eager for such a discrepancy to be discovered, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door to “new physics” and shut some holes in the Model.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant drawbacks, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oh!).
But so far, such differences have not been found in CERN.
Consequences
The benefits of these studies for the daily life of the average person are more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there is none.
At the very beginning of the 1960s, pioneers of laser research in Bell’s labs could not have even guessed what kind of revolution their work would cause.
They anticipated their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally seen as a "laboratory gadget".
Imagine...
And in addition, the application can be found for the toolkit accompanying the study.
For example, the same Uilliard Boyle during his optical research in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although it was not originally intended, now serves as the “eye” for all digital cameras in the world and has earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
Palliative care is the best way to die...
The Commission for a Decent Death in Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate should resume soon, and at this time a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this critical area.
"Debt" tried to look closer.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Monterey.
Prostate cancer, which destroyed him from the inside, gave him a delay of two years.
"I was given five years, I lived seven," he says, between life and death, lying in bed in the shelter of the palliative care of Victor-Gadbois in Beloya, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, it’s impossible to prepare for it,” he says.
The disease does its job: an incredible weakness that prevents you from going to the toilet on your own and even eating on your own.
Sitting at the table, on which there is an appetizing dinner, he gives up and agrees to be helped to take food.
He wakes up, even manages to smile, talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicine, take him to the bathroom.
Courage before an ordinary death.
“My greatest desire to be cured of diarrhea is humiliating,” he admits.
A few hours later, the staff found a cure for this ailment.
“Over the course of our lives, we are taught that a man should urinate standing up,” says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois shelter.
Regressing to a child’s condition is an unbearable humiliation for some.
“It all depends on a person’s ability to accept the decline,” he says.
Since, according to many people engaged in palliative care, important events occur in the midst of this decline.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care facility are all cancer patients.
Forecasts give them a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses does not provide any more care, called “medical.”
Mrs. A., 89, is most afraid of dying "in consciousness from suffocation."
But the disease allowed me to get to know my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I don’t want anything else in my life,” she says before allowing herself to wear a mask that eases her breathing.
She is still waiting in the coming days for the last visit of her son, who came from Italy.
In the shelter Victor-Gadbois with the help of a group of volunteers provide body care and food assistance.
This is the palliative care that remains when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one place in palliative care for every 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little, given that sooner or later we're all going to die.
Here life continues in the best conditions possible, explains Dr. Christian Martel, one of the doctors of the shelter.
Whether it’s physical, emotional, or emotional.
To the dying, we will agree to give a mouthful of brandy or pepsi, as long as he asks.
We no longer force diabetics to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we brought a beer to Mr. H., who died tonight.
In the morning, his son drank this beer in the legs of the deceased.
“We help loved ones, as well as patients,” says Natalie Savar, director of patient care.
In the shelter of Victor-Gadbois, no day is like the previous one.
Next to a 93-year-old man who enjoys his last meeting with his family in the yard, lying on his pillows during a toast to him, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children and tried everything to survive.
“In the last six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christian Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, to care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients who have entered the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor-Gadbois Shelter and the Greater Montreal Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is this large gap in Quebec’s health care system that causes many palliative care practitioners to fear enacting a law legalizing euthanasia and aiding suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by luminaries in the field of palliative care, Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapuant, has been circulating and testifying to their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not effective enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in an ambulance in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to relieve them.
I'm afraid that patients only want to die because they don't get adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists to the last day try to save patients, despite pessimistic forecasts.
Helen Richard's hopes for survival were already minimal when she stopped debilitating chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me she regretted that I was stopping the fight.
She told me that my days were numbered.
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask for death thank the medical staff for not complying with their request, after the palliative care team relieves their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely omnipotent in the fight against pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Palliative Care Society, patients are not susceptible to anesthesia in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until the moment of his death, either from time to time or constantly.
We can no longer pretend that we do not know about these sufferings.
More and more often, patients who fail to relieve pain will be able to have access to palliative sedation.
People who suffer from pain always say the same phrase: “I want to die.”
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want to be euthanized,” it means “I want to feel better.”
