Pay and sell without the help of banks - with Bitcoin
The complete opposite of the current monetary exchange, based on central banks, numbered transactions between the receiving parties with commission fees for their processing.
In addition, as often happens with these technologies, a political vision is obvious: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol of the BitTorrent type, which allows you to exchange files between participants of the same level.
About 200,000 operations have already been registered with 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for making donations or as a means of payment.
Bitcoin’s exchange rate, peaking at $30 (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>23) in June 2011, fell five months later to $2 before returning today to around $10 (the exchange rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the world’s exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency, published in October, was interested in this system.
He describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “competing with the dollar or the euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as "credits" used to promote in video games, which are earned in the course of the game or which can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are simultaneously bookholders, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses, like an email.
Only for each new payment, the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically, using a dual-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction do exist in a public ledger sent across the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It passes through the solution of a mathematical problem sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, receives the privilege of adding this new line.
We are talking about the hashing phase of the file, that is, the conversion of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" it all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is correct.
The transaction thus turns out to be inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, the user very quickly (less than ten minutes) would want to pay twice with the same money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed because they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the prize is regularly split in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible by up to one hundred million, which leaves another reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with increasing computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Sites providing Bitcoin services were attacked, and Bitcoins were stolen from reserves.
“The defect used does not concern the protocol itself,” assures Pierre Noise, who recently launched Paymium, a real-money payments company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this disadvantage.
Major players, such as Wikipedia, refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, allow it.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the account book and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
The "giant sales" were announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” rejoices Ion Holmqvist, who works at Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noise, another author of the manual on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which in this way comes out cheaper.
The owner has better control over his personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, Pierre Noise said, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
“Before Bitcoin is established, it will take some time, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
By the way, the ECB’s report proposes to revise the various risks that are now considered to be heightened if the system is successful.
We left Afghanistan.
What's next?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Capisa and Surobi).
NATO and the U.S. should follow suit at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain control of its territory, and for the Afghans to choose their future without relying only on us.
We were mainly affected by Afghan peasants, whom we regarded as terrorists.
And we ourselves, with 88 soldiers killed, both wounded and mutilated.
The Taliban consists of foreign extremists, former commanders hiding in Pakistan, but also often of peasants who reject the presence of a foreign army, as it was under the Soviet Union.
They want to protect their traditions, old and archaic, even if they are joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
They are tolerated, sometimes assisted by local insurgents, but they will be gone as soon as the West becomes more sensitive.
The withdrawal of the French troops from the base of Nijrab, which I observed from the height of the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, was in order.
Convoys of trucks and armored vehicles accompanied by helicopters reached Kabul without being attacked.
Since the end of 2014, there will be no Taliban invasion of Kabul.
Circumstances have changed since their insurmountable advance from 1994 to 1996.
At the time, Kabul was empty, the country was in flames and blood because of the struggle between the various factions.
Taking control of the country was then perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
Afghan women paid for the gloom of these peasants, in which they were surpassed by al-Qaeda, but their situation has not improved these days.
The former Mujahideen, the Afghan government and the current Taliban are united in their desire to keep women in a subordinate position.
The main characters of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They have turned into dealers, capturing state land, to resell it for construction to returnees who have returned from Iran and Pakistan, taking advantage of the huge US subcontracts.
They are discredited; most of them, by the way, did not even fight themselves.
People, as I have heard in the countryside, want a government that is not made up of thieves.
