These works, with the intensive involvement of local labor, were able to help contain the rebellion: irrigation, wells, drinking water, forest restoration, fruit trees, soil protection and an increase in the area of arable land.
What will we leave in memory of ourselves, spending two billion euros on military spending?
A much more modest budget would contribute to improving the living conditions of the local population, which are very harsh in these valleys, often more than 2,000 metres above sea level.
The Embassy received dozens of written requests for small-scale agricultural work coming from local communities in the province of Kapisa.
In order to get rid of the uprisings led by foreign factions, which the farmers, as they told me, wished for, it was necessary to provide them with a little non-military support, which would be well controlled and would come directly to them.
Difficult Births of the Egyptian Constitution
This is a new risky step by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever on the issue of a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives it extraordinary powers, he has decided to play va-bank.
Surprisingly, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to complete the work.
Egypt has been relying on a preliminary text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal contradictions, for two years now.
This new initiative only increased the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his “autocratic delusion”, continuing “to violate this word” and “to trample on the right”.
In the camp, his followers are confident that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by accelerating the transition process.
The referendum must be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the Brothers to abandon the intention to explain to the Egyptians the text, article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to restore public and democratic legitimacy, while discontent rages across the country.
Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote positively, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since the call for an expedited vote resembles an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: “Either you vote for my text, or I retain extraordinary powers”, which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted for the text yesterday.
Most liberals have not responded to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they knocked on the door feeling unable to convey their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society have done the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, reserve participants, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that in most cases the articles were voted unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, were amused by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around... the time for prayer, since some members of the committee felt that the hours of the Constituent Assembly were incorrectly set.
The text, which was voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The object of universal attention, article 2 eventually remained identical to the article in the 1971 Constitution, which states that “the principles of Sharia are the main source of law.”
Salafist parties, for whom the implementation of Islamic law is one of the main requirements, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would allow for their stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” say the liberals, who see it as nothing but PR.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution occurs through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar a consultative role, in particular with regard to verification of compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pomiet, this is alarming, because “people who are called to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.”
We can see the birth of theocracy.”
Many liberals, moreover, are excited by the fact that the next rector of this university seems to be much less moderate than the current one.
“There is currently no specific religious interference.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulemas, but people with university education, some were trained in the French system," Alexis Bloe, who is preparing a dissertation on the Egyptian constitutional transition, reassures.
But he admits that “there may be ambiguity around Article 220, since the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to “fiqh” [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question may arise as to how competent civil judges are to decide on this.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday has been criticized as it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood claims that they are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the authority of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defense budget will take place not in the Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Also, the trial of civilians in military courts will not be prohibited, despite requests from associations for the protection of human rights.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they considered detrimental to freedom.
Blasphemy remains a liability, and insults are now banned, which can have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for press freedom.
In addition, none of the articles is more about protecting women, emphasizes Heba Moraef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive aspect is the prohibition of torture in article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, the demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state, in turn, will take to the streets on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy places, the Navel of the Earth and the sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and the pristineness of nature.
AiF has identified five of the most important reasons to visit Israel.
Worship the Holy Places
It is worth visiting the Jordan River, in which Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that everyone who enters this “bath” receives God’s grace.
And Galilee is the place of the miracles of Jesus: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on the water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here Jesus appeared before the disciples and after the resurrection.
But most of all the holy places in Jerusalem.
Believers here pass the Way of Tribulation or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin - Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antony, the Pretoria, where there was a trial, and in the streets of the Old City leads to the Temple of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha - to the place of the Crucifixion, the Stone of the Anointing and the place of the burial of Jesus.
Here is the symbolic Christian Navel of the Earth, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem will be erected on the place where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew, from which a cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem is the most sacred place for Jews - the Wailing Wall, left of the temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different confessions leave here notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Take a trip vertically
The ruins of the fortress of Massada remained a secret refuge from enemies, which Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
They are located on steep cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above ocean level.
And only those who are fond of mountaineering can reach them in their own way.
The rest are brought to this historic peak by a cable car.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort Hermon, where in the winter months - a huge influx of tourists.
A shuttle bus delivers to him from the foot of the mountain.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, on the top of the mountain supposedly lived pagan gods.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You don't go to all of them on one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are worth a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains the oldest Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
You should also visit the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
His exposition includes paintings by impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cezanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akko, you can visit the Al Basha Ban museum, which is a few halls of ancient Turkish baths with murals of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea, it is worth visiting the unique part-Rally Museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Dal<0xC3><0xAD> and Rodin.
There are no guides and souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are not accepted.
The fifth - the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells about one of the most dramatic pages of history.
The most tragic section - a children's memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You walk into it and you find yourself in total darkness.
The stars are flickering.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Healing
The three main resort areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
Each of them has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, the Red Sea is bathed even in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 degrees of heat, and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and they swim there all year round.
By the way, this is the most unusual sea in the world is at the lowest point of the planet - 417 m below the level of the ocean.
The azure water in it is brine, easily holding on to the water even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes around are unrealistically beautiful.
They come here to undergo a course of treatment with salt water - rapeseed, and healing mud, and treat health with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes mellitus, to put in order the shattered nerves.
Touching the mysteries of antiquity
They are kept by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
Through it passed the famous Sea Route, connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they also lived a long and happy life.
Tourists love to wander through the narrow streets, named after the signs of the zodiac.
They say if you touch the walls on the street "your" sign, Fortune will become benevolent.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds coming from all over Israel and even other countries for a photo shoot.
And in Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can wander around the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the crusaders.
During the Roman period, Caesarea was the principal city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists on note
When going to Israel, do not worry about your imperfect English: in the country about 30% of the population know the Russian language.
It is better to take money for the trip not in euros, but in dollars, which are easy to exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar - 3.8 shekels).
Urban transport is mainly buses, but Jerusalem has a high-speed tram, and Haifa is the country's only metro line, consisting of six stations and connecting the Lower City with the Upper City.
In fact, it's an underground funicular.
Travel in all types of urban transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can drive with transfers for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport stop working.
On Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels - only kosher food, excluding pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
They offer a large selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts cooked on coconut milk, traditional Jewish humus paste, a variety of sauces, balls of ground chickpeas - phalale, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are a lot of fed cats that valyazhno "walk on their own."
In the evening, they can be seen sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Murlyks love crowded places and do not refuse treats.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $ 37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to 188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus the insurance is $15 a day.
A bicycle rental will cost 15 s. per day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
In 2012, Israel was visited by more than three million tourists from all over the world.
Citizens of the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine came to travel and rest the most.
118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
