While MPs and human rights defenders argue that the law on mandatory language testing will give, scammers have already appeared in the country, selling "lippy" certificates.
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to support the families left behind.
On December 1, the law came into force, according to which every labor migrant will be obliged to pass the exam for knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the field of services, housing and communal services, households and retail.
However, over time, the FMS promises, the tests will become mandatory for all visitors.
At the same time, it will be necessary to surrender not only the language, but also the Russian history, and the basis of legislation.
Knowledge of the language will have to be confirmed in order to obtain and to renew a work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of those countries where Russian is the state language.
They are not subject to the law and people who managed to obtain certificates and diplomas of education before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Benefit, doom and protection of rights
The network of examination points will work under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants will be able to take tests in all cities; more than 160 such centers have already opened in Russia.
The initiative on the introduction of testing was supported by deputies of the State Duma and the FMS.
But human rights defenders, before the law came into force, many times had time to ask the press: what, in fact, will it give?
What will change the obligation of knowledge of the language for Russians and for the visitors themselves?
