Problems arise in migrants without a profession, education, language-skilled, without a medical certificate.
Without understanding the language, - Sebelev is sure, - the future migrant is doomed to face dishonest people, who under the guise of help will shove him "a way" into a terrible narrow barracks, where he and dozens of others will linger for months without food and documents, incubating 12-14 hours a day.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrants.
“At home, they are promised one thing, and upon arrival they are deceived, they take passports, they do not pay the promised salary,” said Tolib Sharipov, the head of the General Directorate of Labour Migration of the Ministry of Justice of Tajikistan.
