However, while many citizens of the Central Asian republics, going to earn money in Russia, admit that not only do not know the language of the country in which they seek, but also on their own, write with difficulty.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the trouble: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford even an intelligent primary education.
After all, their families have nothing to feed their children, not to mention to dress them decently, put them on and equip them for school.
Growing up to adolescence, such guys at the first opportunity go to earnings.
It is difficult if the language is poor, they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
However, with regard to the language law, human rights defenders note one important point.
The tests will only be carried out for migrants who have legal status.
If there is no status, there will be no exam or subsequent official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers still live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome, or Aliens are forbidden to enter"
Many of the visitors claim that getting an official status in our country is not so easy.
The reason is bureaucratic obstacles and all the same language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But fake registration can be done quickly and for only one and a half thousand.
Russian police officers know that we have mostly fake documents, no registration, hence cases of extortion.
"They ask for a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," Tajik citizen Umed Khushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be greedy, buy a painting"
