Such conclusions are provided by a joint inspection of the Czech and German control authorities.
As an example of wrong practice, Peter Nechas's approach to the so-called Schwartz system is cited.
Recently, the prime minister said that the GDP (Civil Democratic Party) will not bother entrepreneurs with checks - is it prohibited or allowed?
“The law should be established in some way, and if it prohibits anything, then the prime minister can not resist the work of institutions, which are charged with the duty to verify and enforce their obligations,” Kala said.
At the meeting of the Audit Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you discussed a joint project between the Czech and German parties, in which the legislation on public procurement of both countries was compared.
What exactly was it about?
This is a parallel test that we started probably two years ago.
Simply put, European legislation states how public procurement should take place, followed by national legislation and then also applied in practice.
All the information was collected and, even with the still unfinished verification, interesting differences were found - in simple terms, the legislation in our country can be "accurate and unmistakable", but in practice, we are inferior to Germany in some respects.
It follows that it is not enough to create more and more detailed rules, it is necessary to focus on the application of the law itself.
And how can this project help you, what does it mean for you?
It is such joint control that can contribute to efforts to stop clarifying laws, reducing and improving restrictions, because it does not lead to a positive result.
Economics means getting the right thing at a reasonable (but not always low) price to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal behavior.
But it is not the fact that we will achieve this by reducing the limit on orders.
Perhaps this system will be filled with “papers” so that those who want to find loopholes in this system will find them much easier than if the restriction had not been reduced.
You are talking about internal problems of practical application of the legislation on public procurement.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there such an organization as our CRU (Control and Audit Office) or does it work differently?
As far as the institutions are concerned, there is the Bundesrechnungshof, which is our principle, and there is also a college that works a little differently, but basically both institutions operate in the same way.
In addition, the powers are somewhat similar, but since Germany has a federal structure, there are audit units at the level of the federal states - in this their system is somewhat different from ours.
BRH can only manage federal money, we have state funds.
Public funds in our regions and municipalities are controlled at the level of the Federal Accounting Chambers.
As for the local legislation, is it easier than we have?
In general, I would not like to compare without specific data, but in some respects Germany can be taken as a sample, but it cannot be definitely said that it is better in everything.
Is it because they are better at controlling?
