Poland and space.
Last week, at a European Space Agency ministerial meeting, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has actively participated in a number of Agency projects over the years.
But Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in flights into space, but this was not always met with understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture of A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933, presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his groundbreaking work "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and André Louis Hirsch Prize for "Introduction to Space".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned space propagandist, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the back of the moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925, a railway track was built in Poland, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket had to be used to accelerate or brake the truck.
Information about this thresher is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about missile arrows.
The study was carried out by the Section of Armament Technology in cooperation with professors Me<0xC4><0x8D>islav Wolfke and Gustav Mok<0xC5><0xBE>icki.
From the surviving materials, it is clear that the studies have reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, work was interrupted.
In 1937, in the specialized press, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter missile, which was proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, appeared, and the following year, the work "Air torpedo rocket and aviation rocket bomb" by author Lelyva-Kzhivoblotsky was published.
Both projects were designed for the military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all projects of military use of missile technology were handled by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Temporary Advisory-Naukowy Committee), which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of its activity the work was terminated due to the outbreak of the war.
The next scientific work devoted to astronautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautics Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time about society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal "Problems", which publishes four volume articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would be engaged in space exploration.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were gaining momentum, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) tried to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and already in the fall of the POA became its full member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the POA, Kazimierz Zarankevich (1902-1959), became the deputy chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PAA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful Meteorological Rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, capable of overcoming a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested at Bledowskyi Void.
This rocket was about 1.4 m long, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could cover 14.5 km, and its task was to observe the high-altitude wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type missiles was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight - 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B - 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Institute of Aviation developed the Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to bring a payload weighing 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Then were built versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution to the problem.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Public Works Act.
The decision sparked a lively debate in society.
It will undoubtedly be interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU, as well as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of multiple, unregulated economic competition.
In essence, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, are in constant conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital along with unbridled financial speculation.
As a result of a significant difference in the cost of labor (wage), price tensions arise.
By this concept one must understand the state when the producer, through the delivery of cheap goods, tries to withstand economic competition by “beating” the cost of a competitor in order to take away most of the market and thus increase his own income.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either moving production abroad, or cheap purchases abroad, or disappearing, resulting in higher unemployment in countries where the cost of labor is high compared to others.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility, including for the unemployment it produces, the inevitable expenditures of the state on social needs grow.
In general, the situation increases the reluctance of the masters of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the social economic and social damage they inflict in the pursuit of profits.
The situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistics.
Unceremoniously methods of private capital create at the level of economies of individual states a situation when governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments give their own populations to private capital, despite the social decline.
This is reflected primarily in the changes in the current legislation.
The aim is to economically compel its people to submit to the dictates of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
It acts as a system of economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment and at the same time serves as a tool for reducing workers' rights in the field of labour law.
The result is an increase in poverty and, at the same time, the difference between the rich and the poor.
In Germany, for several years there has been a public distribution of food to the poor, who are unable to feed themselves with their own labor.
The number of these people is approaching a million.
As part of improving the competitiveness of the German economy, there are constantly cases when employed people receive such a salary that the state must pay them extra to get a living wage.
Such a scandal became known to the public and in the case of additional employees of the Bundestag.
Economic measures in almost all southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation in which people under the pressure of a catastrophic decline in social status are forced either to emigrate, as it was in the 19th century, or to exist on a poor salary at the back of society in the hope that someday private investment capital will come to the country.
The question is, where will it come from?
If capital comes from other EU countries, poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, as the Chinese, Hindu, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian, African still works for a share of European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media argue to nausea that the state cannot participate in the capital of its own economy, that a managed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital insists that the state should not interfere with the economy by governing actions.
Next, the question should be answered whether private capital, which is now practically managing politics and the entire state, is not acting for its own selfish purposes?
The unequivocal answer is yes.
Evidence is the existence of virtually omnipotent and ubiquitous lobbies in all states.
As a result, we have a desperate situation, manifested in corruption, mutual benefit, in legislation where almost everything deserves to be punished, but it is not a crime.
In Germany, the situation is such that state ministries, due to lack of financial resources, entrust the development of draft laws to private law firms that are closely related to industry.
These bills are then approved by the Bundestag.
All power does not come from the people, as the constitution of the Western type says, but from financially powerful groups preferring their own interests.
It is obvious that liberal-oriented democracy now quickly finds itself in such a situation, as described by Appian in The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Days of Caesar and Pompey: “The state has long been disintegrating, and the agencies are engaged in violence.
Takeovers, illegal receipt of favors with the help of stones and swords.
Profiteering and corruption prospered without any prohibitions, and the people themselves went to the elections with a pre-sold vote""...the decent people did not run for the post of ruler at all, after all, one day the state remained without a consul for eight months." .. "They seriously began to say that the only salvation in this terrible situation is autocracy and the need to choose an energetic man.
As in antiquity, our own reckless interests predominate in modern society without taking into account public interests.
Private capital is no longer intended to be used for public purposes.
The current result is no different from the past: the unprecedented decline of the elite without any effort to carry out reforms of a deeper nature.
So the reason for the emergence of fascist and communist regimes we must look for in the reckless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
To date, the absence of these regimes and the existence of a liberal type of democracy can be perceived as a certain pause, after which the next round is expected.
First of all, it is tragic that the current elite completely ignores the consequences of the hundreds of thousands of victims in the future, the humanitarian and social catastrophes that we are already witnessing, along with the crimes against humanity, as we know from old and new history.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a decision, or at least not forever.
Under the pressure of competition at both the international and national and European levels, the Government of the Czech Republic will continue to seek ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic in nature.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the participation of the state in the economy, strengthen the role of citizens in the governance of the state and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
