The movie “Operation Argo”: When there is nowhere worse, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student demonstrators seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the deposed Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the U.S. revolution, who had been the patron of his regime for decades.
The US administration was not expected to have a positive outcome - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because it could have fundamentally undermined the confidence of allies in other countries.
However, to achieve the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was not able.
This was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later amplified by a failed attempt to release the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were finally released 444 days later, after negotiations mediated by the Algerian government.
Their fate caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The defeat in Iran contributed greatly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter in the 1980 presidential election, culminating in the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, “Operation Argo” describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After difficult vicissitudes, they ended their journey at the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to take them out of Iran, with the help of an extravagant cover legend, according to which they drove on Canadian passports as members of the filming group, looking for a place in the country to shoot a sci-fi epic.
Combination of genres
The plan, invented by Evacuation expert Tony Mendes, required Hollywood’s cooperation.
To make the legend credible, specialized magazines wrote about the project of the film, held press conferences, a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
The Affleck film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "film-cineopus", the story of a successful venture, a scam - an example can be a number of films about friends of Ocean.
The moods in the film are constantly changing - on the one hand, documented scenes from Tehran (the titles show iconic historical photos of events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lightened Hollywood passages intersecting with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions - men in suits discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, on the stairs of institutions, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck has managed to relaunch his career.
The ridiculed actor became a respected director, and his play ceased to be the object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third feature film, after the dark detective "Goodbye, Baby, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The City" (2010).
At the same time, this is the first Affleck film that is not filmed in the director's hometown of Boston.
The sense of place at the same time refers to the qualities that raised earlier films of the director above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it at Argo, where Tehran is playing Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, in the reconstruction of real events - the opening scenes of the fall of the embassy impress with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unforeseenness that arise when the story suddenly changes somewhere.
A similar effect Affleck and his colleagues achieve in the scenes fictitious (fake headquarters on the Tehran bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not imply a lot of exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He is quite successful with this few, sometimes he thinks something - there it all turns out not so elegant (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents the impending crisis at the airport of Tehran, and chasing on the runway look quite far-fetched).
The disadvantage of “Argo” is the distraction associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman in the role of Hollywood colleagues are really very charming, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are not the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of drama, it is a film that can be watched with moderate interest, evaluating the production and retro style, recreating the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to capture.
However, this is enough to remind of one, still in a certain sense living history, as well as to testify to the exaggeration of ideas about omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services.
