The EU’s controversial directives include, for example, the mandatory addition of biocomponents to fuel, which is detrimental to nature, as well as a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermostats just because they contain a relatively small amount of hazardous substances, or a directive on the size of a cage for chickens, resulting in a significant increase in the price of eggs this year.
Also criticized was the factual ban on the use of the term "bread oil" or the removal of classic bulbs from the sale.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters long.
The pan-European apparatus often makes decisions under pressure from a trade or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually defended by any state or group of states (the Czech Republic is now even under threat of veto defending the demands of its banks).
The interests of the lobby are as follows: for example, bananas of the highest quality in the European Union were supposed to reach a length of 14 cm and did not dare to show "abnormal curvature".
At the same time, the Commission justified itself by merely harmonising existing divergent national rules that made trade more difficult.
The EU, despite resistance from some states, has nevertheless relaxed standards for fruit and vegetables, citing the fact that existing directives will lead to waste of products.
A candidate for the poll could also be last year's EU regulation, according to which the balloons sold must be provided with a warning that children under the age of eight can not inflate them without adult supervision.
The EU has turned to U.S. research, according to which balloons when playing are a potential cause of death of children through suffocation.
Such a restriction now applies to children under 14 years of age, who are prohibited from blowing into fair windmills.
Funny ideas are born at home.
