The architects of MVRDV prove that real adventures are not only in the imagination - on the example of Speikenisse and its newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
“This building seems fun to me, it looks futuristic, finally we can see something interesting again,” says Lisette Verheig, passing by on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, says, “No, this building is really beautiful.”
But I ask myself, why do we need another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPad, and e-books.
Now no one goes to such old-fashioned libraries voluntarily anymore, right?
Speikenisse, an inconspicuous sleeping town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 people has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this unfortunate circumstance a few years ago, it was decided to contribute to general education and build seven fictitious bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of picturesque painted miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the city fathers realized that they had only one chance to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Winnie Maas of the Rotterdam architectural bureau MVRDV, master of bold column diagrams and author of witty, sometimes even cynical buildings, treated the task with his usual serenity and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury members looked puzzled and shrugged their shoulders, the daring Maas put together a pyramid of size from his original gift and concluded the speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Dear citizens!"
Here it is, my proposal: "Book Mountain" in Speikenisse, the so-called Buckenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain, worth 30 million euros, grew.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, "Book Mountain" was awarded the second prize of the contest "Best Library of the Netherlands 2012".
The project also participates in the national Dutch competition of wooden structures in 2012.
Thus, a faceless suburb, which previously could not offer anything but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, the white facades of which suggest the idea of a dairy plant, became richer on one modern piece of architecture.
But most importantly - in Speikenisse appeared the first in the history of this city public building for cultural purposes.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: a book Eldorado under a cheese cap.
There is only one elevator passing in the center of the mountain range, because true fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glazed on all sides, the room is light and easily visible, the floors of the burnt brick and elegant street lights unmistakably create the feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is perfectly recreated.
Look involuntarily looking for benches, dogs and playing football boys and girls.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
“Usually, book shelves stand along the facades, and in the middle is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless,” says Vini Maas.
We put the classic configuration of space on its head and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The internal space of the book mountain is used skillfully: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical premises.
Black bookshelves are especially pleasing, which serve as wall decoration, railings, and stair railings.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and construction engineers are lost in guessing what kind of unknown material it is.
“We sought to work with secondary materials,” explains Joep Trauborst, project manager representing the Speikenisse community, in accordance with the requirements of the standard.
And once, at an agricultural enterprise in Friesland, we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, an artificial fibrous material of millimeter thickness has been used as a lining under the roots.
It is cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons, after which it can be discarded.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was compressed into a panel four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called landbauplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material, smelling a little like a new car and a little shoe.
There are 105 steps to the top.
Anyone who crosses a path nearly 500 meters long will be rewarded in a literary cafe not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and wooden ficus in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and above all about the correct humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
The Cost of a New Soul
“It’s hard to believe, but this building, despite its many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Trowborst.
For its heating and cooling, the heat of the earth is used.
Although the Book Mountain stands under a glass cap, even on clear days the sun only gets inside for a short time.
Wide farms made of glued wood, located perpendicular to the glass facade, give shade and take on most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned IT skeptic, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verheig was already here.
As well as the teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogard, who called Buckenberg "the soul of Speikenisse, which has long been lacking".
The reason: a few weeks before the opening, each resident was invited to donate one book from his own congregation.
These books were supposed to occupy empty seats on the shelves of the not yet fully equipped library - at that time there were 70,000 books in it.
The idea worked.
The shelves are up.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Vinnie Maas.
“I think that thanks to our invitation, now every resident is somehow connected to this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal task, which in professional jargon is called the creation of identity.
Speikenisse wrote his literary history.
And let them be very young and uneducated.
This is just the starting point for identity building.
Szabo: “The Germans should play a more important role”
Germany abstained in the vote to recognize Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinians’ request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why not?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Now Germany needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that she also does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO carried out this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, moving from the policy, which, so to speak, was governed by the United States, to the German foreign policy itself.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent common policy.
Thus, the Germans find themselves again between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that so far they are only tapping their role, but are on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
The kind of foreign policy that France or Britain pursues.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
This is a willingness to take a position that does not depend on the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are largely different from those of other major states, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, in particular in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elites in the Arab countries.
Either way, it plays a role.
But I wouldn’t give it too much importance, it’s not a completely one-sided connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relations with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States the understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don’t think it was as dramatic a blunder as it was in the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect in this way.
After all, this signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are differing views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has spoken out for a veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European countries?
Because of U.S. domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration, deep down, has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, the government, of course, can not openly take such a position.
I believe that significant differences of opinion are not at all as significant as it always seems.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and its position as the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a unified, non-contradictory European policy, but now it is not.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and are instead forced to act on their own vision of the situation.
This is what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take a leading role in the development of a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
This topic has always been sensitive.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, won’t it really take the lead?
Or is the leading role still difficult for Germany?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes on an important role, a variety of anti-German sentiments are manifested.
The Germans don’t just deal with it.
In fact, this is an old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It should take into account a variety of neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
So, the US influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, then who remains?
