What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, and hepatitis.
Pediculosis and scabies are parasitic STIs.
What are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea are found mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of every five cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydial infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungus), gonorrhea, and the human papillomavirus.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low, but about 20 percent of new HIV infections are in this group.
Among young people, chlamydial infections are significantly more common than among other groups of the population.
According to European data, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
The human papillomavirus is also common among young people.
How does the number of infections change?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory registration.
The incidence of syphilis, according to the Robert Koch Institute, more than doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This is about one-tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate venereal disease?
In infectious diseases, there may be ulcers in the genital area, complaints when urinating, discharge, pain in the lower abdomen, as well as blisters or seals.
However, they are often not accompanied by pain and other symptoms and remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not provide 100% protection.
After all, partially the causative agents of sexually transmitted diseases can also spread through contact infection and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examination, especially with frequent change of sexual partners.
With early diagnosis, you can cure most STIs and avoid distant consequences.
