It was attended by a large number of women under veils and Salafists who shouted: “The people demand the application of God’s law.”
They demanded from Morsi: “Clear the country!” and assured: “The Qur’an is our constitution.”
The struggle for power over the symbolic square on which it all began provoked a state of practically civil war.
Morsi’s followers obviously didn’t want to take that risk.
The Muslim Brotherhood said that both opponents and supporters of the draft constitution spoke out loud and clearly.
Now it is time for the people to decide at the ballot box in which direction the country should go.
The majority for the Islamist project, this is considered a settled case.
"The concept of 'human rights' is never mentioned."
Hafiz Abu Saeda is furious at this forced constitutional process, which, in fact, was supposed to last until February with the participation of all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood while they were in jail or on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he shared their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this he was beaten, sentenced, arrested.
And now the words “human rights” never appear in the new constitution, he regrets in an interview with “Welt am Sonntag”.
Morsi’s expansion of influence across all three branches of power in the state disappoints the lawyer.
These measures are clear blows to the democratic rules of the game and will lead the Egyptians to a new dictatorship.
“Instead of strengthening the civil state, the president has de facto annulled it,” Saeda regrets.
Without civil society, democracy cannot function.
Saeda feels that everyone has left him, even the international community, which looks at the ideological struggle of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
There may be a retribution for that.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns: “You’re creating a monster that you can’t control.”
Norwegian rakfisk: the worst smelling fish in the world?
Norway’s five million people have one of the highest living standards not only in Europe, but worldwide.
Perhaps the secret of this country’s success is somehow related to the local addiction to one extremely sinister fish dish?
Take a few overripe pieces of cheese.
Put them in a pile of dirty and sweaty sports clothes.
Leave them there for a week.
You will get a spiky smell of rakfiska - one of the most famous Norwegian delicacies.
I am in a small town called Fagernes, three hours from Oslo.
Surrounded by snow-covered picturesque views. It is very beautiful, but there is an inextinguishable characteristic smell in the air.
Rakfisc is trout sprinkled with salt and strewn in water for up to a year, depending on what kind of shower you need to achieve.
As twilight thickens and it gets colder, crowds of Norwegians gather for a festival in Fagernes dedicated to this very, let’s say, exciting dish.
“It’s eaten raw and drunk with a glass of aquavit, local cumin vodka,” explains Howard Halvarsen, a local firefighter by profession and part-time “raffisk general” who runs the festival.
All around us, people eat fish cut into small cubes and drink it in large portions of alcohol.
“Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk,” Howard says.
This drink can break the smell.
I'll try a couple of slices.
If you manage to carry a piece under your nose, then everything is not so bad - little different from the portion of sushi that you have been carrying with you on the bus for a long time.
Rakfisk is a Norwegian product from a completely different time, a time of poverty, when, even before the advent of refrigerators, fish were soaked in hermetically sealed barrels of salt water in the autumn.
Then in the deep winter, when the fish was already well and thoroughly frozen, it was extracted and, silencing the perception of alcohol, consumed.
In the memory of the last generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13 percent are immigrants, who are attracted by jobs, high wages and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (an old rival, and not so long ago and a much more prosperous neighbor) come here to work.
Rakfisc is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, albeit somewhat sinister, element of Norway’s past.
It is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich will cost you <0xC2><0xA3>9 ($14).
Norway rarely appears in the world news, and most of the country’s residents seem to be happy with it.
People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, a racist and right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the attack is called “the incident of July 22.”
It is very hard for Norwegians to believe that in their peace-loving country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
Norway’s current prosperity is based on the growth (since the early 1970s) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“But oil is not the only reason for our prosperity,” says Anna, our waitress, carrying trays of aged raffish, a woman with long blond hair and strikingly blue eyes, the embodiment of Nordic well-being.
We are such a people, as you call it, reasonable.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks English well.
We don't like to show up, we're not bragging.
Norway handles its oil very carefully - most of the oil and gas revenues are invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone was making money they didn’t have, Norway was calculating all the costs sparingly.
“As long as you can ski in the winter and go hiking in the summer, that’s enough for happiness,” says Anna.
"And there's a rakfisk," she adds with a carefree laugh.
I'm standing in the snow in line for some food, and I've had enough of rakfiska.
Here's a hamburger with moose meat - it's definitely exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening we are waiting for even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
My hotel hosts a special dinner dedicated to the rafisk, during which visitors vote to determine the best or perhaps the most fragrant fish.
There is a live TV show in which the presenter is shown in a bow tie, surrounded by plates with rakfisk.
It's like a Eurovision song contest.
"So, Thor-Jürgen, what assessment did you make of the best fish in the mountains?"
"Yes, Howard, here's our assessment."
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls off the chair, maybe taking the aquavit.
Or maybe just smelling the fish.
Mexican President Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto has a difficult start to his career.
As Mexican President-elect Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to take a look at the difficulties he will face and the mixed expectations of his country’s population.
Traffic in Mexico City is in a particularly dire state.
The city is overloaded with transport at its best, and since Monday, steel barriers have been erected, cutting through several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was not done to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, will put on a presidential tie and take over the reins of the country.
He faces a difficult task.
Mexico has achieved good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, which is now laying down its powers, but the country is mired in a war on drugs that has already claimed about 60,000 lives in six years.
“My government is declaring to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence,” Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama earlier this week in the Oval Office of the White House.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Prior to such statements, Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto’s political career developed alongside the President of the United States as governor of his home state of Mexico City.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and vast state surrounding the country’s capital, opinions about the new leader were divided.
Rectangular man
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, it is remembered with warmth.
Residents credit him with the revival of tourism, the development of the resort sector and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, which are strikingly different from the roads with holes and pits that were previously on this site.
The signs with his name hang on the modern building of the sports center and on the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We are connecting with him hopes for real and serious change,” says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman from the Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We look forward to the real and decisive changes that are so urgently needed by our country, especially in the area of security and economic development.
After 81 years in power, the PRI party was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence from the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high hopes for Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
In addition, he denies the accusations of inconsistency that the new president was put forward by the opposition.
He is very straightforward and very committed to embodying his vision for the future of the country.
He is an excellent statesman, and above all, a man who can listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea of the former governor.
The municipality of Nessaualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Nessa, is the most striking contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under highway overpasses, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality also bear the harsh nature of this metropolis.
Earlier this year, troops were deployed to appease drug trafficking gangs in those areas, and violence against women was particularly acute.
In the desert near the extensive landfill only in the last two years, several dozen bodies of murdered women were found.
More than 1,000 women were killed in Mexico State during Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto ' s governorship, well above that in the infamous city of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, whose name has become a household name when it comes to the murder of innocent women.
According to opponents of Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, it can be said, at best, that during his tenure as governor, he failed to cope with the problem of the murder of women.
In the worst case, his administration is accused of completely ignoring the problem.
A resident of a concrete house similar to most houses in this stale neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles to hold back tears by showing me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her cohabitant killed her.
“When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed before,” recalls Ms. Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten and her body was already stiff.
Mariana's mother retells this story, and the portrait of her daughter looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to the crucifix, which has only one word: justice.
This, they said, was denied to the family.
“State officials treated me like an old gossip, dissatisfied with a disturber of calm.
They want people to simply accept what they say and shut up.
But it is wrong, it is not possible, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around," she says.
Putting on the presidential tie on Saturday, President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto with her will take on a difficult responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has pledged to make addressing the issue a priority during his reign.
“I hope he will be exactly the same president he was as the governor,” said Olvera, a congressman from Valle de Bravo of the PRI party.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nesa fear the most.
Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, the indictment says.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's allegations of poor conditions of detention.
During the hearing, particular attention was paid to Manning's stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense demands that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's conditions of detention were cruel.
The U.S. Army has been accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of many opportunities to file a complaint about ill-treatment, which he said he had been transferred while in a military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Feyn said that the records of Manning’s weekly visits by prison administration officials for nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of the defence's motion to terminate Manning's case, on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment, was conducted the day after Manning stated that while in custody he intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During Friday's hearing, prosecutor Feyn and Manning reviewed the reports that were filled out after Manning's visits by administration officials during his time at Quantico Prison, where he was under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Feyn asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he regarded the prison administration's treatment as "excellent" and the general terms of detention as "very professionally organized".
The reports reviewed do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning being directly asked about the conditions of his detention, Feyn argues.
Manning replied that he had expressed oral concern about these problems and that the administration who had visited had discussed them with him and had stated that they would be dealt with, but had not recorded it in writing.
“They recorded ‘no problems’ (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn’t mean I didn’t raise the topic in the conversation,” Manning says.
A military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his mistreatment in January 2011 during a meeting of a commission examining the suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to get rid of the “injury prevention” regime and to ease the conditions of detention.
Representatives of the military leadership explained that a limited regime of detention - to a level lower than the surveillance regime for the purpose of preventing suicide - was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
“I wanted to let the administration know that I’m okay so they can cancel the injury prevention regime... so that my standard of living improves, from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait, and that one day he lost consciousness due to the severe heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult when you are not allowed to know how your fate is decided and what is happening in the outside world.
“My world has shrunk to Camp Arifjan base, to the size of my prison,” Manning said on Thursday.
“I thought I was going to die in this cage.”
While in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell—at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day—alone.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only a mattress, blanket, hats, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move because sleeping or even just lying down during the daytime was forbidden by the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, light constantly beat into his eyes, penetrating the outside of the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned over in bed at night, then, according to him, he was awakened and forced to turn over on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint about Manning's mistreatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, a judge questioned Manning about a statement he made while testifying on Thursday that after one night he was forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of security guards and other inmates at a morning checkup.
Manning said he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Answering the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he should throw a blanket he could cover, but admitted that no one directly ordered him to throw it.
Manning said on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer that he could have used a rubber band or flip-flops to injure himself, but did not.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, hats and glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he experienced during his detention and significantly reduce the term of detention if Manning is found guilty by the military court, which is due to begin its trial early next year.
The defense said it plans to offer Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes and challenge other charges as excessive.
The resumption of the hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was detained in Quantico under the rules governing the detention of detainees under the strictest possible regime.
The charges brought against Manning included aiding the adversary, unlawfully facilitating the disclosure of data on the Internet, the transmission of national defence information, and the theft of state property or documents.
If convicted on all counts of indictment, he could face life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of an American of Mexican descent.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarrette believes that Mexicans of American descent are torn between the two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrival corridor, approached the border control area, and froze on the spot.
The signs pointed to two queues: one for Mexicans and one for Extranjeros.
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in Central California and have been called Mexican all my life.
It’s just a conventional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish and my friends in New York call themselves Italian.
Later, I settled on the elaborate construction of an "American of Mexican descent."
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather’s homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complex constructions.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can’t get rid of the American accent.
That's why I got my American passport and queued up for Extranjeros.
I recalled this story a few days ago when Mexico’s newly elected President Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were the usual issues for the meetings of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto was eager to talk about the Mexican economy’s rise, which would allow Mexicans to now, with the same success, stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to sign a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is a difficult and filled with old grievances.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and, with a shotgun, forced its leaders to give up half of their territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is worth only some U.S. statesman to speak a word of criticism towards Mexico, the press and among the elite of Mexican society immediately spread complaints that the Americans infringe on the sovereignty of neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are full of belligerence.
Mexico’s relationship with more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States is the most difficult.
Do you want to talk about insults?
That's enough.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities for themselves in this country, and those for whom there are no such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican descent for only one reason: at some point in their family history, someone — a father or grandfather — did not have the opportunity to realize themselves in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often they were Mexicans of a certain type - dark, low-educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember that.
Mexico sees it differently.
Today our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we studied in good schools and got a good job, but we must not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider our own.
United States of America.
In addition, we know that most members of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We respond to them in the same way.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as non-real Mexicans.
We do not speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is due to failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they would not have left.
We would not be behind the silk curtain now, finding a full life in the United States, but losing spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and this reminds me that there are some frictions between real Mexicans and Mexican-Americans — Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly, and Mexican-Americans are offended.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintances of Mexican descent do not feel belonging to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
When you get the best of two worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we are Americans.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relations were already not sufficiently complicated, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican Americans to work as Mexico’s ambassadors and represent Mexico’s interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends about what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit, and we could persuade political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
It's not gonna work.
Too many insults in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, the rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country so beautiful.
I'm sorry, but deal with it yourself, amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican Americans are still resentful of how their relatives were treated in Mexico recently.
Yeah, I guess.
I think we have more in common than I thought.
The Old Battles in the New Middle East
A ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is a lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
Sounds familiar, meaningless debate about who started it; many buildings turned into ruins; killed over 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis; for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip fell in the vicinity of the Israeli capital Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that the Israelis and the Palestinians are hopelessly stuck in their eternal conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated differently, but the events of the “Arab Spring” have stirred up many established realities in a rebellious storm, and the Palestinians and Israelis have failed to stay away from the whirlwind that has shaken the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their struggle will be even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope for a way out of this deadly impasse.
A war without winners
At first glance, the current situation does not give grounds for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, will be implemented, the clashes this week have only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
Leaders of the Hamas Islamist movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will say they have forced Israel to retreat despite their losses.
Despite the fact that some of the group’s leaders were destroyed and 1.7 million residents were blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of our planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing in popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements grows in the Arab world, Hamas has new powerful and wealthy friends.
A resurgent regional leader, Turkey, once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim nations, has backed Hamas, followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamically developing states in the Persian Gulf.
The triumphant supporters of Hamas declare the creation of an Islamist crescent around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, ruled by the paramilitary group Hezbollah, to Syria, in which increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow Bashar al-Assad, and further to Jordan, where the king’s authorities threaten Hamas’s allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on Israel’s southern borders, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where under President Mohammed Morsi the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid little attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, by contrast, is an organization largely similar to Hamas, and its leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic relations, Hamas could become a significant player, whose voice will not be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to opposite conclusions.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
Israel’s Iron Dome anti-missile system justified the costs of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
Citizens of Israel can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, the United States has remained true to its unwavering position; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for the start of the latest round of violence.
Another important factor is Israel’s economic prosperity, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, who largely ignored the peace process.
Although some 30 Israelis have died from rockets fired from the Gaza Strip since 2004, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part at the expense of a wall that enters the territory of the West Bank - a significant part of the unrecognized Palestinian state - and protects Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the January 22 elections - has teamed up with even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of supporting the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If you give them all the power in the West Bank, won’t they start firing rockets at Israel from there, as their fellow Israelis in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and firmly suppress any attempts to lift their heads.
Proponents of the hard line may win; however, their calculations may be refuted by the Arab spring.
While Islamists, who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere, do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel must no less take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic changes take place in Arab countries, depriving Palestinians of the right to self-determination is a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect – the growth of the Arab population – only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to be paid for by the growing dissatisfaction of the international community.
Both sides need an external impulse.
There remains the only solution that is relentlessly called for by sane representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two states and the concession of territories by Israel in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not too impressive in the short term, that the ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which has long had to decide to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, are more than ever in a position to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in the recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama must also play a role in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he still shows a reluctance to get involved.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States is vitally interested in stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the Uniform Cigarette Packaging Act came into force.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and images of disease-affected parts of the body stand out in contrast on the dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
Australia’s first ever law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and color design of different brands with the same box of dull-olive color with terrible pictures of the affected body parts and images of children whose health is undermined by smoking their parents.
In addition to various pictures and inscriptions warning about the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packs introduced mandatory from this Saturday are the names of stamps that are printed in the same fine print.
These are the world’s toughest conditions for packaging tobacco products.
The Australian federal government says the aim of the measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving them of this bad habit of fashion status.
This decision was based on the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26, in 99 cases out of 100 never become smokers.
“It’s obvious that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies try to convey through packaging,” Health Minister Tania Plibersek explains, citing studies that show that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated in children with the idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest proportion of smokers in the world, so these changes will not particularly affect the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering such measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies argue that this will only increase the share of the black market in which cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
“This law will lead to serious consequences other than those conceived by its initiators,” said Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of fake products from China and Indonesia will supply much more of these products for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, new laws promote business growth.
Sandra Ha from the small family company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that the demand for cigarettes and silicone cases hiding unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (almost from scratch) since two months ago companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost the case.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about six thousand products to wholesalers and expects a new batch.
This is a good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among the part of the population to which these measures are directed.
After Australia passed a number of laws that made it illegal to advertise cigarettes on television and support them for sporting events, as well as prohibiting sellers from displaying cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from placing ads on the web, but it cannot restrict foreign websites from doing so.
“If you sell tobacco products and you only have this little loophole, the idea of promoting your product online will seem extremely tempting to you,” explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of brand reviews written on behalf of supposedly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is it really the work of an ordinary citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he did not regret his efforts and time and made a video, or is there an advertising company behind it?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco claims that the industry is now more busy adapting to the new rules than advertising.
Tobacco industry has even taken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these States are making claims within the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that trade relations between all these countries and Australia are very insignificant.
A WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanya Plibersek, the government discussed with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first to introduce mandatory posting of photographs warning of the dangers of smoking.
Now this rule is adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia are demonstratively disobeying innovations.
These pictures don't bother me.
I'm just not paying attention.
“Just grab a cigarette and hide the pack in your pocket,” explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumor on the pack.
Honestly, the only thing that can make me quit is my little daughter.
James Yew, the head of the King of the Pack tobacco store in central Sydney, claims that the same packaging has complicated the task of placing goods on shelves.
