“The government had to take and completely ban cigarettes, we would then say: what to do, all right, it’s over, we close the store,” he says, throwing his hands up.
Missing in the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
On this Thanksgiving, I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had mechanical problems and was replaced by another plane, which we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and there will not much help either books, magazines, iPhones, or even duty-free shops.
Recently, however, more and more scientists and specialists in child development speak in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations for us and for our children to miss is not so bad.
This forces the brain to be distracted by interesting related topics, which may contribute to creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some screen, the benefits of boredom pass by us.
Maybe we need to be bored?
Oh, yeah.
And at the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
I used to think that boredom was a relatively recent invention when people had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
“In fact, boredom can boast of a very ancient history,” he says.
On the walls of Pompeii are found Latin inscriptions about boredom, dating back to the first century.
The question remains, however, how do we understand boredom?
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying the research materials on the topic and asking a question to a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came up with the following definition: boredom is when people “want but can’t do what would satisfy them.”
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn’t do something they’d like to do.
With apathy, you don’t want to do anything.
The main thing in experiencing boredom, he says, is “attention disorder and the associated mood deterioration and the feeling that time is slow.”
The description of boredom may seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible link between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the world and circumstances, and people experiencing depression see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel bored when it’s really hard to focus on something.
In their study, “The Unoccupied Mind: Defining Boredom in terms of Attention,” published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a recording of a voice reading the journal.
Some participants also heard the loud sounds of a non-relevant television program included in the next room, others heard the same sounds at a low volume, so that they could hardly be disassembled, and the third group listened only to the recording of the voice without a foreign soundtrack.
Those participants who heard the low-volume TV noted that they were bored, more often than others - they had difficulty concentrating, but they did not know the reason for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, interrupting attention can be boring, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neurology at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, "for example, looking at the flow of products on the conveyor in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom."
It is believed, he continues, that when people start rocking on a chair or drawing stunts on a piece of paper, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions just help not to relax physically.
“The study showed that children who are not forbidden to squirm and turn learn better and remember more information than children who are asked to sit quietly,” said Fenske.
At some point, we all get bored: with a flight delay (as in my case), listening to monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting film.
However, different people show a different degree of propensity for boredom.
In the 1980s, to measure such individual characteristics, researchers developed a special "scale of propensity to boredom".
To determine the score on this scale, questions and statements are used, for example, "A lot of what I have to do is monotonous and monotonous" or "I am too much interested, so there is not enough time for anything."
Using such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys are more likely to miss girls, says Stephen Wodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially if there are a variety of external stimuli.
In general, however, teenagers often miss.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day using a pager.
32% of teens said they were bored at school and during homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what similar data on boredom would be now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that “adolescents have a peak in boredom,” mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Back to my original question: is boredom useful?
Sometimes not, because in extreme manifestations, it can, as research shows, push people to absurd and dangerous physical activities, risky gambling or the abuse of certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have wondered about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovic, who has devoted more than two decades to the study of this problem.
“That’s how our brains tell us to do something else; it’s boring,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
However, this very brain does not always know exactly what to do.
If you’re bored and you put that energy into playing guitar or cooking experiences, you’ll make yourself better.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will stop being bored, but he will not learn to fight boredom on his own or in any other way to manage his time and work,” says Professor Fenske.
"And such self-regulation skills are used in a variety of situations," he says.
Your child learns not only to do something on his own, he also learns self-control in general.
I don't think boredom needs to be extolled.
However, it is not worth considering it as a bad thing either.
Rather, you should learn to feel comfortable even outside the continuous flow of actions and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
“We see it as a way to get bored more often, with boredom being an extremely unpleasant, insatiable desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
“In the modern world, we are used to constant overstimulation of the senses,” he says, “and when silence comes, we get lost and don’t know what to do.”
It is not yet clear how the new law on the legalization of marijuana in the state of Colorado will apply
Anthony Orosco, a nineteen-year-old footballer and community college student in southeastern Colorado, is charged with a criminal offense that will soon be completely legal throughout the state: keeping a small portion of marijuana and the tube he smoked it in.
Mr. Orosco says that he was in Lamar with his friends once in September and was driving in a car on the prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer found marijuana in the car, Mr. Orosko was summoned to court for possession of drugs and possession of a device for drug use - minor offences, each of which was fined $100 - and a court date was set.
“We are being treated like criminals,” says Mr. Orosko.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that has been going on for weeks since the state of Colorado voted to legalize the use of marijuana in small amounts for entertainment, the decision of hundreds of small court cases depends not so much on the law, but on the place of consideration.
Accusations of minor marijuana offences have already been dropped in hundreds of cases here and in Washington State, which has taken a similar action.
Police stations have already stopped prosecuting people aged 21 and older for keeping small doses, which will be considered legal as soon as the law comes into force in a couple of weeks.
However, in the more conservative counties of Colorado, prosecutors have decided to review existing marijuana-related cases and continue to hold the drug accountable.
At the same time, in some cities from the suburbs of Denver to the mountainous areas of the West voted to prevent the emergence in their places of new, state-licensed stores for the sale of marijuana.
“It’s all happening so fast that I don’t even know what to expect next,” said Daniel J. Oates, chief of police in the town of Aurora, east of Denver.
Representatives of the controlling bodies in the state of Washington are also puzzled by scratching their heads.
They will have to establish rules to determine how to license the cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done before December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, good or bad, is ahead of most other states in resolving marijuana use issues, first for medical purposes and now for entertainment.
“There’s a more orderly market in Colorado, so they’ll set a good example,” explains Brian E. Smith, a representative of the Washington State Board of Alcohol Regulators.
But now no one can do more, admits Mr. Smith, than put forward some suggestions and hope that it will work.
“We don’t have a real precedent to focus on,” he says.
The Washington state bill, called I-502, will enter into force on December 6 and will put the state into a state of uncertainty for a whole year, when the state licensing system does not yet exist, and the right to own marijuana is already legalized.
And there are still difficult technical aspects that need to be addressed during this period, for example, how to find a balance between the state's order to "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with a ban on the sale of it at a distance of 1000 feet from schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens.
“It will be particularly difficult to place licensed marijuana businesses within cities, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs,” explains Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the recently established marijuana legalization research group.
On November 21, the chief of police, Oates of Aurora, sent an e-mail to his subordinates that the city's prosecutor's office would no longer hold persons over the age of 21 accountable for possession of a small amount of marijuana, and that the police would stop accusing people of these violations "from now on".
Police chief Oates said the police would monitor the city's compliance with the rules governing medical marijuana growers and would prosecute illegal drug traffickers and distributors.
The Weld County Prosecutor in northern Colorado, Ken Buck, is taking a more rigorous approach to the issue.
After the vote on the bill, he stated that the prosecutor's office would continue to prosecute possession of marijuana, mainly in order to encourage its users to undergo treatment.
At the moment, 119 people are charged with possession of two or fewer ounces of marijuana, although many are also charged with other violations.
"It is the duty of our institution to prosecute acts that are considered criminal at the time of their commission," Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The reaction was mixed even in places like the rural district of Mesa, where voters rejected a proposal to legalize marijuana.
Grand Junction Police, the largest city in the county, no longer holds adults accountable for possession of a small amount of the drug.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger backed the decision, but also decided not to drop the charges in the already opened cases related to the possession of marijuana.
“I believe that ensuring compliance with the law until it changes is our direct duty,” he says.
While 55% of Colorado residents voted in favour of the decision, the inclusion of marijuana for entertainment in the state and legal system will not be easy.
And the contradictory reaction of residents in different parts of the state has exposed the ambiguity of the attitude of local authorities to the state's experiment with marijuana.
“Country prosecutors have a cultural barrier to this,” explains Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer representing marijuana convicts and a local representative of the National Marijuana Law Reform Organization.
“They’ve been chasing people for so long that they can’t really accept that it’s not a crime anymore,” he says.
Colorado and Washington, the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana in the same way as alcohol, are destined to become an experimental field nationwide to test the very idea of drug legalization.
Proponents of legalization and state officials plan to expand the territory of legalized trade, but at the same time they are cautiously waiting for instructions from the federal authorities, who still plan to consider the sale and cultivation of marijuana as a federal crime.
Proponents of marijuana legalization hope that the Justice Department will concede on this issue.
Despite several resonant arrests of drug traffickers and medical marijuana users, the federal government has in most cases given a benevolence to the medical marijuana trade in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Anti-drug agents are unlikely to break into homes to confiscate a small bag of marijuana, but they are unlikely to turn a blind eye to state-regulated recreational marijuana stores that are allowed under the new law, according to Kevin A. Sabet, a former anti-drug adviser to the Obama administration.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for the actions of the federal authorities.
Even before the presidential election, some local administrations approved a moratorium on the opening of new marijuana stores, which would not have been able to open sooner than a year later.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the western part of the state, put forward a six-month ban on the marijuana trade, which is likely to be approved next week.
“We don’t want to be in a position to give someone a license, and then it will cause serious problems at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
The city voted against the amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the results of the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still a lot of unresolved issues.
Petronella Wyatt: I got out of Oxford for being a conservative.
The persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
For as long as I can remember, I have always dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and elder brother studied in Oxford and described it as the best educational institution in the world, a modern analogue of an ancient symposium, laying the two foundations of civilization - freedom of thought and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of studying history at Worcester College, Oxford, in the late 1980s, I packed my suitcases and left, which resulted in the first real scandal of my life.
My father couldn't stand it and cried.
Friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I dropped out of college because I didn’t like my classmates having sex in the next room.
Writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I had to leave because I had to drink from the sloppy cups.
It wasn't really that funny.
I ran away.
Yeah, I ran away because I was systematically bullied and intimidated.
Not at all because of my rather unusual name or the fact that I studied in a private school.
I was poisoned for only one reason, and in this illustrious cradle of enlightenment it seemed true barbarism and blind fanaticism: my father, now the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a well-known adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I myself was a supporter of the Conservatives.
You might ask, why do you think about it now?
According to the latest data, a new generation of students, adhering to the center-right views, is subjected to the same harassment.
This institutionalized and ever-growing hatred of conservative students in Oxford is so strong that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection of their rights as that granted to disabled, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives at Corpus Christi College’s student club in Cambridge say they are “often actively isolated, personally assaulted, and made to feel unwelcome guests” because of their political views.
They want to introduce an additional representative to the College Equal Rights Committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was only aggravated by the recent BBC 2 documentary about politics in the student environment, Wonderland: Young, Smart and Right, in which conservatives were presented by eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
The film featured Joe Cooke, the former president of the Oxford University Conservatives Association, who rides in a rolls Royce, wears a silver suit and a cane with a silver hoodie.
At other universities, conservative students complain that they are being made “scapegoats due to higher tuition fees.”
Luke Black, 20, vice president of the University of Nottingham Association of Conservatives, said in an interview with a Sunday newspaper that “the university environment is increasing a disorientation towards the left.
“People who don’t even know us think we’re the brazen and impunity-ridden children of rich parents.”
Samuel Roberts, 21, a student at the history faculty of Corpus Christi, in which the request for increased protection was filed, calls such an atmosphere "uncomfortable", and Stephanie Cheryl, 19, the new president of the Oxford University Conservatives Association, says that the attitude of members of the student club to right-wingers has deteriorated significantly.
“This poses a threat to both the atmosphere of intellectual discussion and the normal life of club members,” she said.
For the first few weeks in Oxford, I was not just in the minority, I was alone.
I entered there in September 1986, a shy and shy eighteen-year-old girl.
Oxford was feverish with hatred for the Conservative Party.
A year earlier, the university had voted to deprive former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree due to a reduction in the budget allocation for higher education.
In such an atmosphere, even the Stalinists would be uncomfortable.
In the first days of the freshman week, when students got to know each other and the teachers, I felt for the first time that was waiting for me.
I did not know that teachers not only looked through their fingers at the harassment of conservative students, but also took part in it with pleasure.
Political issues — the miners’ strike, privatization, and the government’s refusal to impose sanctions on the apartheid government in South Africa — penetrated the wooden walls of the audience.
At my first seminar, I had to translate the French text of the eighteenth century into English, and I was not ready for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said the teacher, now the late Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
The text was difficult for me, I was stunned.
Harry Pitt was a very gall-like man with a cake-like face.
“The Thatchers don’t teach French in principle, or they just don’t have enough brains?” he asked.
The other students sneered.
I had tears in my eyes.
“I advise you to take a few initial French lessons in your spare time, unless you are, of course, very busy spinning around in society,” Pitt said.
I went back to my room completely unhappy.
That night in college, I was sitting at lunch alone; then someone slapped me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year English-language student who introduced himself as a member of the University’s Association of Conservatives.
“I know who you are,” he said politely.
- Unfortunately, the case is as follows:
Anyone suspected of sympathizing with conservatives will be bullied.
It's not easy for me, and in your case, they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's going to be harder for you.
Most first-year Conservatives pretend to be Labour.”
Later, at a local pub, I tried cowardly hypocrisy.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything Margaret Thatcher said.
The trick didn't work.
A freshman from the Faculty of Philosophy, Politics and Economics, who studied at Eton himself, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contagious."
Other students picked up his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
"How do conservatives have sex?" asked one of them.
"They're kicking each other, aren't they?"
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the criminal prosecution was abolished in the sixties.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life in Oxford?
Or do I have to meet with like-minded people only under the cover of the night?
Will I be forced to become a Labour leader and hide my true beliefs?
The next three years seemed like hell, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only teacher in my college who did not hide his conservative views was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history.
He was hated not only because of his membership in the Conservative Party, but also because he was Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of her speechwriters.
He barely showed up in college.
He despised him for his provincialism, pettyness, and commitment to a Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997, he took a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began to travel to Oxford from my parents’ home in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and unbiased friends of the capital.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and explained the reason.
He didn't believe me.
During his studies in the forties there were adopted any political views.
“But it’s the best university in the world,” he complained.
- They can't do that, except in the city of slumbering spires...
Even my communist friends have always behaved impeccably.”
His wet eyes were blurred.
“Don’t make hasty decisions.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
You'll break my heart if you drop out of college."
I was exhausted by my constant trips to London and my emotional defenses weakened.
My friend, also a conservative, could not stand the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
The following week, during a seminar, when another history teacher took me seriously as an “enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
In my heart of shame, I confessed that my parents had brainwashed me and called them “old fools.”
The respite was short.
The last nail in the coffin of my career in Oxford was destined to kill my father.
At that time, he wrote two columns each week for publications owned by Rupert Murdoch.
My door was locked.
I didn't leave, and five minutes later my pursuers surrendered.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and boarded the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a weasel and a rag.
But at eighteen, no one should become the object of such anger and intimidation in an educational institution.
The sad thing is that it was Oxford, which not only released fourteen Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind the undeserved reputation of a university that values equality and free-thinking.
“Valentino prefers elegance to fame.”
About the exhibition “Valentino: Master of Sewing”, which opened this week in London, ABC is talking with Nati Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemica and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, the former residence of Queen Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this during the opening of Valentino: Master of Sewing, a triumphal retrospective exhibition that brings together more than 130 high-fashion dresses created by his “home” over the past 50 years.
"I love this palace," he says with his unique Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of the story, the only character of which is "il Signore" Garavani, but it could not be written without his eminent clients.
Valentino has always felt enchanted by the rare and distant world of the nobility.
The first hall of this exhibition, open until March 3, abounds in personal letters and photographs signed by the most aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, including Marie Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from a modest tailor from the town of Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of the international “elite”.
Being in love with the royal court is not a bad thing.
“They don’t at least put out their cigarette butts on your gorgeous carpet, like some great pop stars do,” says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornewitz.
In the 60s and 70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is an outstanding host and welcomes guests with generosity and elegance.
“We all loved coming to his chalet in Gstaad,” explains Heini’s ex-wife Thyssen, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenia Niarchos.
Valentino always preferred elegance to fame.
And yet, he is a star.
Valeria Mazza, representing Valentino
Argentinian model Valeria Mazza recalls a charismatic fashion designer.
One day we went to dinner at his house, it was after the fashion show in the square of Spain in Rome, many years ago.
Among the twenty guests were Sharon Stone and John F. Kennedy Jr.
Valentino's style manifested itself in everything - in every detail of his apartment, in its furnishings, in food, in music.
“Valentino made each guest feel important and loved,” recalls the “top model” whose work with the fashion designer began in 1995 during the Paris Fashion Week.
“He never goes out of fashion because his sketches are real works of art,” she concludes.
Pedigree Parade
Garavani's life is not a story of obsessions, but of falling in love with complete reciprocity.
He loves people with good upbringing and high titles, and they love him.
One of the galleries of Somerset House was turned into a glamorous catwalk of sixty meters in length, which offers a change of roles: the visitor takes the place of models and must defile the catwalk, contemplating the "viewers" of dreams that sparkle with masterpieces from Valentino, such as the dress that Jacqueline Kennedy chose for her Sweatshirt.
In this audience of models shine names such as Sibylla of Luxembourg, Gloria von Thurn und Taxis, Mette-Marit from Norway, Rosario from Bulgaria or Sofia Habsburg.
Nati Abascal and fashion designer, in 2006
Many of these clients say that the first Valentino - like the first love, "it is impossible to forget."
I remember him beautifully.
These were trousers, shirt, "vest" and jacket from the autumn-winter collection 1971-1972.
“It was a gift he gave me,” says Nati Abascal, one of the designer’s muses.
"I prefer him to the rest for his femininity, for his great love for women, because he emphasizes our beauty," the former Duchess of Feria added.
I really like the colors he uses: they have a lot of light and they “fit” to his face.
The proportions are perfect.
Princess and fashion legislator Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg also can not forget the first time she dressed in Valentino.
When I was a teenager and lived in Italy, I dreamed that I would have an age and a reason to put on one of his evening toilets.
The time finally came in the late 1990s.
I bought my first dress from Valentino to wear it for the holiday at the castle of my cousin, Prince Edward de Lin.
It was a red dress, with a skirt with frills, a "corsage" in fold and a strapless neckline.
“It was a dream that came true,” says Rodrigo d’Arenberg’s widow.
“Valentino is indifferent to fashion, his passion is timeless,” explains the Italian aristocrat who lives between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
Princess d'Arenberg keeps her festive dresses from the fashion designer with "maximum care... because the dress is not just a dress, it is also a collection of memories accompanying him."
The "King" of Fashion
The grand finale of the exhibition at Somerset House is Marie-Chantal Miller's wedding dress for her wedding to Pavlos of Greece in 1995.
It took four months of work and 25 "girls" (as the designer calls his seams) to make this outfit of ivory silk with pearl inlay, twelve kinds of different lace and a plume of four and a half meters.
According to journalist Susie Menkes, the greatest authority of the specialized press, the dress represents a milestone of high fashion at the end of the 20th century, "the return of clients from the upper world".
Intoxicated for many years by the "lifestyle" of the elite, Valentino is now his own best representative.
The Grand Cross Cavalier (a badge of distinction of the highest rank in Italy), the Labour Cavalier, the Commander of the Order of Arts and Letters, awarded the Order of the Legion of Honour, Garavani collected as many honors as any of the spouses of his clients.
“My attention has always been drawn to his sophistication, his calmness, his neat and impeccable appearance,” Dr. Arenberg recalls.
The last time I saw him was a month ago at a dinner party at the Musée d'Orsay.
He was sitting at the table with Countess Jacqueline de Ribe, my great friend.
“He was flawless, time doesn’t exist for him.”
If that's what the princess says...
The most difficult profession in the world: miners from Kawah-Ijena
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano along steep rocky paths
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others are literally working in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living mining sulfur in the Kawah-Ijen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day Anto descends to the very bottom of the crater, where sulfur gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes when in contact with air.
Having broken off huge pieces of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, rolls the baskets on his shoulders and carries them up a steep rocky road.
Up to the summit of the volcano, which is 2,386 meters high, is only 250 meters, but exhausted loaders need more than 40 minutes to climb the turtle step, with difficulty maintaining balance and carefully tapping the road, so as not to fall and fall from the cliff.
They know that one wrong step could cost them their lives, as happened to a tourist from France who broke down from the rocks of Kawah-Ijen a few years ago.
Kawah-Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulfur they mine
Once on top, they pave their way between tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales, which the mining company placed a little higher, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
It is the PT Kandy Ngrimbi, an enterprise that has operated this volcano since 1960 and, better not to say, its workers, to which it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) for each kilogram of sulfur.
Then it sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to petrochemical industries, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used for making matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
“Since carrying 70 kilograms is the norm, we earn about 46,000 rupees (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.8) for each walk,” explains Anto, who usually carries three daily carryovers.
