Hector "Khetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Avid basketball traveler Hector "Khetin" Reyes has been associated with this sport for more than 60 years and, thanks to him, traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico remember as many basketball histories as Hector "Heathin" Reyes.
And before a brain hemorrhage chained him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, as a small-scale player, a Major League basketball player, a commissioner and head of the BSN with the Bayamon Cowboys, and president of the Basketball Federation.
“I’ve played many roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time as when I was president of BSN, CEO of the National Team, and president of the federation in the 1990s,” Reyes recalls during Primera Hora’s visit to his home in Bayamon, where he has lived with Isabel, his faithful wife, for over 50 years.
“Basketball was my life.”
Reyes does not exaggerate by making this assertion.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and memorabilia collected during his long journey, testify to this.
Bayamon in the heart
With the greatest emotion, he retains those who remember his journey through the Cowboys, from the mid-1950s as a player until 1982, when he was 15 years old as a co-agent or contract agent.
“These were the best years I’ve enjoyed the most because I’ve had the opportunity to be part of eight Cowboy Championships since 1967, as an agent, co-agent or executive.
There were many years of joy, including five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one in 1981, the year Jerome Minsey made his debut at BSN.
From that moment on, Kuko Ortiz became the head, who was a great administrator,” Reyes said.
I remember Gene Bartow, who was on his way here and at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), telling me, "I have a very strong player for you, 6'7".
"Would you?"
And that was the start of Minsey, one of the best players that Puerto Rico had.
Bartov then recommended sniper Raymond Gauss, who received citizenship and became one of our best bombers.
I remember saying that if Minsey had brought the championship to Bayamo, Gauss would have helped win another one.
I enjoyed the Cowboy Championship with Gauss, but at a distance, because by 1988 I was already the head of the federation.
By that time, I preferred to enjoy his achievements and the achievements of Minsey in the national team.
I remember the first time we won against the United States during the Olympic qualifying tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, in which we got fourth place and it had to be bronze, if not for the Canadian referee who forced us to replay the final game, Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best team you've ever seen?
She is among the best, as well as the one who won from the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the one from the 1991 Pan-American Games in Cuba, when we won gold and broke up the U.S. national team, which was quite similar to the one that won bronze at the World Cup.
Not only did Minsey, Gauss, Ram<0xC3><0xB3>n Rivas, Fico Lopez and Piculina (Ortis), but also the young (Javier) 'Tonito' Colon and James Carter, the brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario 'Chichote' Morales, who was unable to participate in the 90s due to a wheel injury.
The team, which may not have been the best in terms of personnel, but brought us a gold medal and great joy, was the team of the 1995 Olympic qualification tournament in Neuquen, Argentina.
With role-playing players like 'Canito' Nieves, Pablo Aliseo and young Rolando Hurruitner in exchange for players temporarily suspended for disorder in the Pan-American Championship of Mar del Plata, we won gold against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it was Piculin Ortiz.
His performance in international tournaments is impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level as Piculin has.
And this is without taking into account his career in the various leagues in which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's a very difficult question.
We had a very good youngster, including Julio Toro, Flora Melendez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
From a young age, I really like the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you consider to be your main achievement in the federation?
Participation in the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and that in the early 90s in BSN there were up to 17 teams in a season.
What do you have left to do?
There were things I wanted to implement, for example, the regionalization of smaller categories.
For example, that the boys from Ponce play only in their area and only against teams from other parts of the island in the national playoffs.
Now the guys are traveling and playing too much, and that's superfluous.
At least I see the fruits of mandatory certification and a course for managers, officials and judges.
It gives me pleasure.
What are you doing now?
Most of all, I listen to music, watch music videos of my era on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to basketball matches.
And, of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Icabel, who has always been with me.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Fort Worth, Texas, became world famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.", in the Dallas television series, in which he portrayed a businessman without principles, evil and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series Dallas became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new season of Dallas, died Friday night of complications caused by cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., a Dallas production studio.
“Larry is back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, playing the iconic role he loved the most,” his family said.
Larry’s family and closest friends were with him in Dallas at the Thanksgiving Fair.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and in the sequel, was next to Hagman when he died at the Dallas hospital, her spokesman Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, cheerful, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him very much.
“He was an original person and lived a full life,” Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis in 1992 and he admitted to drinking for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in his liver and underwent a transplant.
Long before Dallas, Hagman gained fame on television for his role as a decent type in the light comedy I Dream of Jeannie, which aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he plays Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive jinn girl played by Barbara Eden, and starts living with her under the same roof.
He was also the protagonist of two rarely aired comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included well-received roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the delightfully disgusting J.R. that brought Hagman to the pinnacle of fame.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its surroundings aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
