It also helped to attract a record audience to the series at that time.
When the answer was given in the November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers watched it and turned Dallas into the second most watched entertainment program in history, after the 1983 MASH finale, which attracted 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Christine (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
J.R. interrupted her and then threatened to charge her with prostitution if she did not get out of town, but others also had reasons to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing as an insatiable corrupt man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest businessman and an unfaithful husband who wanted his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be treated.
“I know what should be on J.R.’s gravestone,” Hagman said in 1988.
It must be said, "Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
It's the only deal he's lost.
Victoria Princepal, also the heroine of the original series, recalled on Friday Hagman as someone "huge, both on and off the screen."
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us who have been lucky enough to know and love it.
